---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { proposals, delegates } from "../lib/data.ts";

// Strip any trailing slash so we can append path segments without doubling or
// dropping the separator; see the note in `layouts/Base.astro`.
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");

// Kept as a string so Astro renders its braces and quotes as literal text
// rather than interpreting them as JSX expressions.
const usageCode = `import { proposals, delegates, processStages } from "@tc39/data";

proposals;     // every ECMA-262 and ECMA-402 proposal
delegates;     // the delegate roster, keyed by abbreviation
processStages; // the maturity-stage definitions`;
---

<Base
  title="Overview"
  description="Structured, typed TC39 datasets — a single source of truth for proposals, delegates, and the process stages."
>
  <h1>TC39 Data</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Structured, typed datasets for TC39.
  </p>

  <p>
    Today this information is spread across semi-structured documents in several repositories:
    proposals as Markdown tables in
    <a href="https://github.com/tc39/proposals">tc39/proposals</a>, the delegate list in
    <a href="https://github.com/tc39/notes/blob/main/delegates.txt">tc39/notes</a>, and the working
    process as an HTML <a href="https://tc39.es/process-document/">process document</a>. This project
    aggregates that information into a single, machine-readable, typed representation generated from
    the upstream repositories and maintained by hand thereafter.
  </p>

  <div class="cards">
    <a class="card" href={`${base}/proposals`}>
      <div class="num">{proposals.length}</div>
      <div class="label">proposals</div>
    </a>
    <a class="card" href={`${base}/delegates`}>
      <div class="num">{Object.keys(delegates).length}</div>
      <div class="label">delegates</div>
    </a>
  </div>

  <h2>Using the data</h2>
  <p>The three datasets are exported as typed values:</p>
  <pre><code>{usageCode}</code></pre>

  <h2>Schemas</h2>
  <p>
    The canonical, machine-checked definitions live in
    <a href="https://github.com/tc39/data/blob/main/src/types.ts"><code>src/types.ts</code></a>. The
    three datasets are shaped as follows:
  </p>
  <dl class="schema">
    <dt><code>proposals</code> — <code>Proposal[]</code></dt>
    <dd>
      Each proposal has an immutable kebab-case <code>id</code>, a <code>name</code>,
      <code>url</code>, and <code>specification</code> (ECMA-262 / ECMA-402 / ECMA-404); a
      <code>stage</code> that is one of <code>0</code>–<code>4</code> or a terminal status
      (<code>rejected</code>, <code>withdrawn</code>, <code>abandoned</code>, <code>subsumed</code>);
      <code>authors</code> and <code>champions</code>; and the list of committee
      <code>presentations</code>, newest first. Stage 3 / 2.7 entries may carry test262 coverage, and
      Stage 4 entries an expected publication year.
    </dd>
    <dt><code>delegates</code> — <code>DelegateMap</code></dt>
    <dd>
      Maps each official delegate abbreviation to a record of the delegate's <code>name</code>, an
      optional <code>github</code> username, and an optional <code>affiliation</code> (the TC39
      member organisation they represent).
    </dd>
    <dt><code>processStages</code> — <code>ProcessStage[]</code></dt>
    <dd>
      Each maturity stage (<code>0</code>–<code>4</code>) with its <code>status</code>, the
      <code>entranceCriteria</code> a proposal must meet to enter it, and the stage's
      <code>purpose</code>, taken from the process document.
    </dd>
  </dl>

  <p>
    An author, champion, or reviewer is in turn either a TC39 delegate (referenced by the
    abbreviation that keys into <code>delegates</code>) or a community member (a full name and
    optional GitHub username).
  </p>

  <style>
    .schema {
      max-width: 70ch;
    }
    .schema dt {
      font-weight: 600;
      margin-top: 1rem;
    }
    .schema dd {
      margin: 0.3rem 0 0;
    }
    pre {
      background: var(--surface);
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
      overflow-x: auto;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      line-height: 1.5;
    }
    /* Reset the inline-code chrome inside a code block. */
    pre code {
      background: none;
      padding: 0;
      font-size: inherit;
    }
  </style>
</Base>
